The revelation that Mark Felt was the storied source who helped set in motion the events that ended a presidency not only resolved one of the United States' great political mysteries, it liberated a gallery of other high-profile figures from decades of speculation. But then-deputy White House counsel Fred Fielding, onetime Nixon aide Alexander Haig, speechwriter Patrick Buchanan and many others who have been mentioned as possible candidates -- in some cases based on circumstantial evidence at best -- may finally face fewer questions about the famous disclosures of over three decades ago. 